article.headline: Holy Cross 41, Dartmouth 15
article.story: WORCESTER, Mass. (AP) -- Dominic Randolph engineered three long scoring drives in the first half to help Holy Cross overpower Dartmouth, 41-15 on Saturday. The Crusaders (4-2, 1-0 Patriot League), constructed scoring drives of 79, 63 and 80 yards in the first half. Randolph completed a 14 scoring pass to open the scoring. But Dartmouth (1-4, 1-1 Ivy League) tied it 7-7 when Tom Bennewitz scored on a 10-yard keeper. Dartmouth was plagued by penalties (14-111) and Randolph, second in completions in the Football Championship Subdivision, capitalized. He led Holy Cross to two touchdowns in the second quarter, setting up scoring runs by Terrance Gass (1 yard) and Mike Kielt (12 yards). Trailing 24-7 early in the third quarter, the Big Green tried to rally when Bennewitz completed a 42-yard pass to Brian Evans on Dartmouth's first possession. A penalty, however, set them back again, forcing another punt. The Crusaders responded with a 7 play-60 advance, capped off by Randolph's 9-yard scoring run. He then found Thomas Harrison for a 4-yard scoring pass to put the game out of reach, 38-7. Evans caught a 30-yard pass from reserve quarterback Alex Jenny for Dartmouth's second touchdown. Matt Partain scored Holy Cross' school record 49-yard field goal at the halftime gun.
